# GitHub shipping and README hygiene

When you fix, adjust, upgrade, or enhance anything in this repo:

## 1. Push to GitHub

- Do **not** leave completed work only on the local machine.
- After changes are verified, **commit** with a clear message (why, not just what).
- **Push** to `origin` on the appropriate branch (usually `main` for production fixes).
- Production deploys from `main` via Railway (Dockerfile) — merging/pushing triggers deploy.

Only skip push when the user explicitly asks to keep work local or review before push.

## 2. Update READMEs in the same change

Update documentation **in the same commit/PR** when behavior, setup, or ops change:

| Area touched | Update |
|--------------|--------|
| Repo-wide / deploy / env | Root `README.md`, `AGENTS.md` |
| API server, MCP, Bullhorn | `artifacts/api-server/README.md` |
| Customer portal, Clerk auth | `artifacts/portal/README.md` |
| Support / triage workflow | `docs/support-triage.md` |
| New package or artifact | Add or extend a `README.md` in that package |

If no README exists for the area, add a short one rather than only updating `AGENTS.md`.

## 3. What to document

- New or changed env vars (names only — never secrets)
- Setup steps (Clerk, Railway, DNS, Bullhorn)
- User-visible behavior (portal login, enrollment vs dashboard)
- Breaking changes or migration notes

## 4. Do not

- Commit secrets (`.env`, API keys, tokens)
- Create markdown files the user did not ask for unless they are the README for the code you changed
